<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>CAM AIR FOUNDATION BRAKES - BRAKE ADJUSTMENT - ROCKWELL AUTOMATIC SLACK ADJUSTERS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="3">
        <title>ROCKWELL AUTOMATIC SLACK ADJUSTERS</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>There are two different pawl designs on the Rockwell automatic slack adjuster.
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400526">Figure 26</hotlnk>
                    illustrates a pawl design that has to be removed before manually adjusting the brakes.
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400527">Figure 27</hotlnk>
                    illustrates a later design which has a pawl button that when raised will disengage the pawl, so the
                    pawl does not have to be removed to manually adjust the brakes.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f0400526" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0400526" filename="../figg04/g0400526.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px"/>
            <caption>Figure 26. Rockwell Pawl Assembly</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. MANUAL ADJUSTING NUT</callout1>
                <callout1>2. PAWL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f0400527" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0400527" filename="../figg04/g0400527.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px"/>
            <caption>Figure 27. "Pull" Pawl Button On Rockwell Automatic Slack Adjuster</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>On slack adjusters that DO NOT HAVE THE "PULL" PAWL BUTTON, if you do not remove the pawl
                    assembly, you will damage the pawl teeth when you turn the manual adjusting nut.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the adjusting pawl assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0400526">Figure 26</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">On vehicles with the "pull" button design pawl, insert a small screwdriver under pawl
                button. Lift button at least 1/32 inch to disengage pawl assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0400527">Figure 27</hotlnk>). Remove screwdriver to engage pawl when finished with
                adjustment.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>If the pawl button is not lifted (disengaged) when adjusting nut is turned, the pawl adjuster
                        will be damaged.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Rotate the adjuster nut until the lining contacts the drum.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn the adjusting nut in the opposite direction 1/2 turn.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure the distance from the center of the large clevis pin to the bottom of the chamber (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0400528">Figure 28</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0400528" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0400528" filename="../figg04/g0400528.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 28. Rockwell Clevis Adjustment</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a pry bar to move the slack adjuster so that the lining is against the drum. Measure the
                same distance again. The difference between this measurement and the measurement in step 4 is the "free
                stroke."
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn the adjusting nut until the "free stroke" is between 5/8 - 3/4 inch (15.9 - 19.1mm).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check the adjustment. Apply the brakes and hold the pressure. With the pressure at 85 psi,
                again measure the distance from the center of the large clevis pin to the bottom of the chamber.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The difference between the measurements in steps 4 and 7 is the adjusted chamber stroke.
                Turn the adjusting nut so that the adjusted stroke is as short as possible, but not so short that the
                "free stroke" is too short and the linings drag. The adjusted stroke
                <emph type="bold">must not</emph>
                be greater than the dimensions shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="hl0400506">Brake Adjustment Stroke Table</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <table id="hl0400506">
            <title>Brake Adjustment Push Rod Stroke (All Automatic Slack Adjusters)</title>
            <tgroup cols="2">
                <colspec colname="1" colwidth="2.75in"/>
                <colspec colname="2" colwidth="2.75in"/>
                <spanspec namest="1" nameend="2" spanname="s1t2"/>
                <thead>
                    <row rowsep="0">
                        <entry colspan="2" spanname="s1t2">
                            <para>MAXIMUM STROKE AT WHICH BRAKES MUST BE ADJUSTED. 80 - 90 PSI AIR PRESSURE IN THE AIR
                                CHAMBER. CLAMP TYPE AIR CHAMBERS. CAM BRAKES.
                            </para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Chamber</para>
                        </entry>
